# Approach
- Here the approach is pretty simple Always the number of Open brackets must be Greater than or equal to the closed ones and in the end we must have a balanced parantheses.
>- The Decision tree of this approach would be like as shown below in the picture.

![pic1.png](https://assets.leetcode.com/users/images/9ca0631b-cc21-4ebc-b3e8-d91f71cf61e8_1681154610.15714.png)

- As Above we can observe how the recursion tree is constructed now we push the end product $i.e$ when `open == close == n` we would push the string into the vector of string and `return` the function.

>This would be the most obvious way to solve these type of question and also there are some solution of a type where bitmasking is used in common but currently we stick on to this type of solution which is enough in most of the interviews.

# Complexity
>- Time complexity: Here the Time complexity would be $$O(2^n)$$ and this is because we cannot optimise the recursion call via Creating a Dp array or something so we have to try all the possiblities which results in Exponential complexity i.e $$(2^n)$$.

>- Space complexity:Here the Space complexity would Just be storage space complexity of $$O(n)$$ due to stack space and vector of string storage space.

# Code
```C++ []
class Solution {
public:
    void gen(vector<string>&vs , string &s , int n , int open  , int close)
    {
        if(open == close && open == n-1)
        {
            vs.push_back(s);
            return;
        }
        if(open < n)
        {
            s.push_back('(');
            gen(vs, s , n , open + 1 ,close);
            s.pop_back();
        }
        if(close < open)
        {
            s.push_back(')');
            gen(vs,  s,  n , open , close + 1);
            s.pop_back();
        }
    }
    vector<string> generateParenthesis(int n) {
        vector<string>vs;
        string s;
        gen(vs , s , n+1 , 0 , 0);
        return vs;
    }
};
```
```java []
class Solution {
    public List<String> generateParenthesis(int n) {
        List<String> result = new ArrayList<>();
        StringBuilder sb = new StringBuilder();
        dfs (n, 0, 0, 0, sb, result);
        return result;
    }
    private void dfs (int n, int left, int right, int index, StringBuilder sb, List<String> result) {
        if (left == n && right == n) {
            result.add (sb.toString());
            return;
        }
        if (left < n) {
            sb.append ('(');
            dfs (n, left + 1, right, index + 1, sb, result);
            sb.deleteCharAt (sb.length() -1);
        }

        if (right < left) {
            sb.append (')');
            dfs (n, left, right + 1, index + 1, sb, result);
            sb.deleteCharAt (sb.length() -1);
        }
    }
}
```
```python []
class Solution:
    def generateParenthesis(self, n: int) -> List[str]:

        def dfs(left, right, s):
            if len(s) == n * 2:
                res.append(s)
                return 

            if left < n:
                dfs(left + 1, right, s + '(')

            if right < left:
                dfs(left, right + 1, s + ')')

        res = []
        dfs(0, 0, '')
        return res
```


