            for(int j=0;j<i;j++){
                vector<string>left=dp[j];
                vector<string>right=dp[i-j-1];
                for(auto &l:left){
                    for(auto &r:right){
                        dp[i].push_back("("+l+")"+r);
                    }
                }
            }
        }
        return dp[n];
    }
};
```

solutions.content:
Instead of using backtrack - which is a little bit hard to handle - I used a Dynamic Programming method that does not involve recursion. 

The gist is as such:

We create the parenthesis array for n by adding "()" inside of, and in parallel with, another "()" for every string element in the "n-1" parenthesis array. 

This may look a bit confusing. Let me explain using an example. 

The "n=1" array is a single "( )".

To create the "n=2" array, we add another "()" both inside of, and in parrallel with the existing "()". Therefore we have such: [ "( )( )", "(( ))"]

To create the "n=3" array, we do the above operation to each and every element in the "n=2" array. 

So, for "( ) ( )", we have "( ) ( ) ( )" , "( ( ) ) ( )", and "( ) ( ( ) )". 
And for "( ( ) ) ", we have " ( ( ) ( ) ) "and "( ( ( ) ) )".

Therefore, for n=3 we have an array that reads :

["( ) ( ) ( )",  "( ( ) ) ( )", "( ) ( ( ) )",  "( ( ) ) ", " ( ( ) ( ) ) ", "( ( ( ) ) )"]

Note that sometimes, you may end up creating duplicate entries. Luckily we can use a hashset to remove them automatically.

when n =4, we repeat the same operation to EACH AND EVERY element in the n=3 array.

```
  public List<String> generateParenthesis(int n) {
        List<String> first = Arrays.asList("()");
        if (n == 1) return first;
        for (int i = 1; i < n; i++) {
            HashSet<String> set = this.processStrings(first);
            first = new ArrayList<>();
            for (String ss : set) {
//                System.out.println(ss);
                first.add(ss);
            }
        }
        for (String s : first) {
            System.out.println(s);
        }

        return first;
    }


    private HashSet<String> processStrings(List<String> strings) {

        HashSet<String> set = new HashSet<>();

        for (String s : strings) {
            this.processString(s, set);
        }
        return set;
    }

    private void processString(String s, HashSet<String> set) {
        int index = 0;
        while (s.indexOf("()", index) != -1) {

            index = s.indexOf("()", index) + 1;

            String newString;
            String newString2;
            if (index < s.length() - 1) {

                s.substring(0, index);
                s.substring(index + 2);
                newString = s.substring(0, index - 1) + "()()" + s.substring(index + 1);
                newString2 = s.substring(0, index - 1) + "(())" + s.substring(index + 1);

                set.add(newString);
                set.add(newString2);

            } else if (index == s.length() - 1) {
                newString = s.substring(0, index - 1) + "()()";
                newString2 = s.substring(0, index - 1) + "(())";

                set.add(newString);
                set.add(newString2);
            }
        }
    }
